{
  "title": "Deploying Machine Learning Training Loops with FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide demonstrates how to integrate machine learning (ML) training loops into a FastAPI application using Python 3.12+. The example provided utilizes the popular Scikit-learn library for ML tasks.",

  "key_points": [
    "Utilize FastAPI, a modern web framework for building APIs in Python",
    "Integrate machine learning training loops with FastAPI for model training and updates",
    "Leverage Scikit-learn, a widely-used ML library in Python",
    "Demonstrated example uses Python 3.12+ features for improved performance and efficiency"
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\n\
from fastapi import FastAPI\n\
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n\
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression\n\
app = FastAPI()\n\
\n\
data, target = load_iris(return_X_y=True)\n\n\
model = LogisticRegression()\n\n\
@app.post('/train')\n\ndef train(x: list[float], y: list[int]):\n    model.fit(x, y)\n\n\
@app.get('/predict')\n\ndef predict(x: list[float]):\n    return {'prediction': model.predict([x])[0]}```"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required for this example to leverage newer features and improvements in performance.",
    "FastAPI v0.72.0 or later is recommended for integrating with Python 3.12+"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "This example provides a simple demonstration and should be considered as a starting point. Real-world applications may require additional considerations such as data preprocessing, error handling, security measures, and more.",
    "Ensure to handle large datasets appropriately to avoid performance issues when deploying your FastAPI application."
  ]
}
